---

# Data Preprocessing

Before training the models, extensive preprocessing was performed on the dataset.

The preprocessing pipeline included:

* Resizing all images to 224×224 pixels
* Normalizing images using ImageNet mean and standard deviation
* Splitting the dataset into:

  * Training set (70%)
  * Validation set (15%)
  * Test set (15%)
* Converting images into tensors
* Loading data efficiently using PyTorch DataLoader

To improve generalization and reduce overfitting, data augmentation techniques were applied during training, including:

* Random horizontal flipping
* Random rotation
* Random cropping
* Color jittering
* Random resized cropping

These augmentations helped the model learn robust visual features from different image variations.

---

# Deep Learning Models Implemented

Several convolutional neural network architectures were implemented and compared during the project.

## 1. ResNet18

The first model implemented was ResNet18. This architecture uses residual connections that help train deeper neural networks without suffering from vanishing gradient problems.

Two versions were tested:

* ResNet18 trained from scratch
* Pretrained ResNet18 using transfer learning

The pretrained model achieved significantly better performance because it was initialized using ImageNet weights.

---

## 2. MobileNetV2

MobileNetV2 was implemented as a lightweight and efficient model optimized for faster inference and deployment on low-resource devices.

This model uses:

* Depthwise separable convolutions
* Inverted residual blocks
* Linear bottlenecks

MobileNetV2 provided a good balance between model size and accuracy.

---

## 3. EfficientNet-B0

EfficientNet-B0 was the best-performing model in the project.

The architecture uses compound scaling to balance:

* Network depth
* Width
* Resolution

Advantages of EfficientNet-B0:

* High classification accuracy
* Smaller number of parameters
* Better feature extraction capability
* Efficient computational performance

The model achieved very high classification accuracy on the test set.

---

# Transfer Learning

Transfer learning was one of the most important techniques used in the project.

Instead of training models from scratch, pretrained ImageNet weights were used as initial weights. The models already learned useful low-level visual features such as:

* Edges
* Textures
* Shapes
* Patterns

The final classification layers were replaced with new layers suitable for the 45 remote sensing classes.

Fine-tuning was then performed on the dataset to adapt the models to satellite imagery.

This significantly improved:

* Accuracy
* Training speed
* Convergence stability

---

# Training Process

The models were trained using GPU acceleration.

Several training techniques were used:

* CrossEntropyLoss with label smoothing
* Adam optimizer
* Learning rate scheduling
* CosineAnnealingLR scheduler
* Early stopping
* Gradient clipping

Training metrics such as:

* Training loss
* Validation loss
* Accuracy
* Precision
* Recall

were monitored during training.

Model checkpoints were saved whenever validation accuracy improved.

---

# Knowledge Distillation

Knowledge distillation was also implemented in the project.

In this technique:

* EfficientNet-B0 acted as the teacher model
* MobileNetV2 acted as the student model

The teacher transfers knowledge to the smaller student model using softened probability outputs.

Benefits:

* Smaller model size
* Faster inference
* Improved MobileNet performance
* Better deployment efficiency

---

# Model Evaluation

The models were evaluated using several metrics:

* Accuracy
* Precision
* Recall
* F1-score
* Confusion Matrix

Performance comparisons were made between all implemented architectures.

The EfficientNet-B0 model achieved the highest performance among all tested models.

---

# Grad-CAM Visualization

To make the system more interpretable, Grad-CAM visualization was implemented.

Grad-CAM helps visualize which image regions the model focuses on while making predictions.

The generated heatmaps highlighted important areas such as:

* Buildings
* Roads
* Rivers
* Forest regions
* Runways
* Residential structures

This helped verify that the model was learning meaningful spatial features instead of random patterns.

---

# Model Optimization

Several optimization techniques were applied to improve deployment efficiency.

These included:

* Dynamic quantization
* Static quantization
* ONNX export
* ONNX Runtime inference

The optimized models achieved:

* Faster inference speed
* Lower memory usage
* Reduced model size

while maintaining high accuracy.

---

# Web Application Deployment

A full web application was developed for the project.

The application allows users to:

* Upload satellite images
* Select different trained models
* Predict scene categories
* View confidence scores
* Visualize Grad-CAM heatmaps

### Frontend

Built using:

* React
* TypeScript
* Tailwind CSS

### Backend

Built using:

* FastAPI
* ONNX Runtime

This created a complete AI-powered remote sensing analysis platform.

---

# Challenges Faced

Several challenges were encountered during the project:

* High similarity between certain scene categories
* Large dataset size
* Long training times
* GPU memory limitations
* Overfitting during training
* Difficulty distinguishing visually similar classes

These challenges were addressed using:

* Transfer learning
* Data augmentation
* Efficient architectures
* Regularization techniques
* Learning rate scheduling

---

# Project Results

The project successfully demonstrated that deep learning models can accurately classify remote sensing scenes from satellite imagery.

Key achievements:

* High classification accuracy
* Successful comparison of multiple architectures
* Lightweight deployment-ready models
* Explainable AI visualizations
* Interactive web application integration

EfficientNet-B0 achieved the best overall performance, while MobileNetV2 provided efficient lightweight deployment capabilities.

---

# Conclusion

This project demonstrates the power of deep learning and computer vision in analyzing remote sensing imagery. By combining transfer learning, advanced CNN architectures, model optimization, and explainable AI techniques, the system achieved accurate and efficient scene classification.

The project also highlights the practical applications of AI in:

* Environmental monitoring
* Urban planning
* Agriculture
* Geographic analysis
* Smart city systems
* Disaster response

The final system provides both high performance and real-world usability through an interactive web-based deployment platform.
